.Microscopic Model calculations.
A set of eight detector telescopes,
each 10 degr. apart., were mounted on two movable arms
on both sides of the beam line. The possible angular
range was 20-115 degr. on the right and 70-165 degree
on the left. A 10-12 Si(Li) detectors were actually
mounted during a run,and the best eight of these were
used in collecting data.
The energy resolution varied between 100 and 150 keV,
of which about 50 keV could be attributed to beam
spread.
The electronics were developed to handle simultaneously
16 deltaE - E telescopes,two beam intensity monitors
and a polarimeter.
* Two detectors placed at 40.degr. above and below the
beam served as monitors of beam intensity
Energy uncertainty (no description in the

The Saclay Sector-Focused Cyclotron.
The polarized ion source was used. The neutral
polarized beam is now ionized outside the cyclotron in
an ionizer of new design.
Extracted beams were generally 10-30 nA,with a
polarization of 70-80%. The sign of the polarization
was reversed every 0.2 sec.
It was not convenient to obtain absolute cross sections
since no Faraday cup was used.
Errors of ~10% have generally been assigned.
This is larger than the statistical error, but it is a
conservative estimate of the reproducibility of the
data points at angles where cross sections were
measured by several counters. (These errors arise
primarily from differences in solid angle and detector
efficiencies and did not affect the polarization
measurements.)
